	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Price volatility and expansion raise financing problems in Ghanaian cocoa sector  </h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 April 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>USDA, in a recent annual report on cocoa in Ghana, forecasts Ghana’s cocoa production at 1 million tonnes for the marketing year (MY) 2011/12 (compared to 1,004,190 tonnes in MY 2010/11, and 650,940 tonnes in MY 2009/10). This is based on favourable weather, improved farming practices, continuing government support, and road rehabilitation works which facilitate the delivery of cocoa to the ports.</p><p>Ghana’s high cocoa production in 2010/11 was in part attributable to smuggling of cocoa beans from Côte d’Ivoire. This is a source of concern, since the lower-quality beans from Côte d’Ivoire could potentially undermine consumer confidence in the premium status of Ghanaian cocoa beans, which currently attract a price premium of US$50–100 per tonne.</p><p>The Ghana Cocoa Board (Cocobod) has a monopoly over the purchase and export of cocoa beans in Ghana (although licences are issued to both private traders and the government-run Farmers Cocoa Inputs Company), and undertakes careful quality control to ensure that premium price quality standards are maintained. It also secures loans for crop financing, with the backing of a government guarantee.</p><p>Government pricing policy seeks to ensure that producers receive ‘at least 70 percent of the Free On Board (FOB) price’ of cocoa bean exports. According to USDA, ‘this price incentive has encouraged cocoa producers to increase production and to manage their farms as a business enterprise with the requisite gains.’</p><p>In terms of value-added processing, there are four cocoa processing companies in Ghana, which process beans into liquor, butter powder and cake. ‘About 90% of all processed cocoa is exported whilst the remaining 10 percent is used in the production of confectionery products.’ Ten companies currently produce chocolate, cocoa beverages, cocoa powder and other chocolate confectionery, ice creams and chocolate drinks. Supplies to local processors fell in 2009/10 from 99,559 tonnes to 65,275 tonnes ‘due to the scarcity of the light crops cocoa beans’ which are normally reserved for local processors. According to USDA, from 2005 to 2010 ‘the total installed processing capacity of cocoa in Ghana has increased from 85,000 MT to approximately 220,000 MT’. The 2009/10 shortages have greatly reduced capacity utilisation in the local processing sector, which is a major source of concern to local processing companies.</p><p>USDA points out that price guarantees for cocoa producers leave the economy vulnerable to declining cocoa prices, in a context where the sector contributes 30% of total export earnings.</p><p>Press reports in March 2012 indicated that Ghana’s government was facing ‘huge financial losses in the cocoa sector’ as a result of low global cocoa prices and the expansion of production in response to government efforts to support the further development of the sector, via input supply programmes.</p><p>Meanwhile on 14 March 2012, members of the European Parliament adopted a resolution calling on the EC ‘to get tougher in negotiating trade agreements’ on the issue of child labour in cocoa production. The resolution calls for creating ‘accredited, third-party-audited traceability for the supply chain’. Calls have also been made for a labelling scheme for cocoa, so that consumers ‘can vote with their wallets to end child labour’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>USDA, ‘Ghana: Cocoa report annual’, <i>GAIN Report</i> No. GH1202, 15 March 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Cocoa%20Report%20Annual_Accra_Ghana_3-15-2012.pdf" target="_self">http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Cocoa%20Report%20A...</a></p><p><i>Public Agenda </i>(Accra), ‘COCOBOD introduces hi-tech fertilizers to farmers’, 9 March 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201203121152.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201203121152.html</a></p><p><i>Euractiv.com</i>, ‘MEPs call for end to child labour in cocoa trade’, 15 March 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.euractiv.com/consumers/meps-call-child-labour-cocoa-trade-news-511516" target="_self">http://www.euractiv.com/consumers/meps-call-child-labour-cocoa-trade-new...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Given recent initiatives to reform cocoa marketing in Côte d’Ivoire and concerns over the impact of the smuggling of lower-quality cocoa beans into Ghana, there would appear to be a need for closer cooperation on quality standards, handling and even pricing policy. Currently the cocoa producer price in Ghana is over 50% higher than in Côte d’Ivoire (3,280 cedis or FCFA918/tonne compared to FCFA600/tonne – €91.5). While this encourages Ghanaian cocoa farmers to invest in expanding production and carefully managing their crop to produce top-quality cocoa, it also encourages cocoa smuggling from Côte d’Ivoire.</p><p>High Ghanaian producer prices appear to be based on an overoptimistic take on international cocoa price trends. In 2010 and 2011 the average annual cocoa price was US$ 3,131 and US$2,978/tonne respectively. With increased use of forward selling it was hoped to lock in high prices and sustain producer incomes during an election year (some 25% of the projected crop was sold at favourable prices and secured a syndicated loan for crop financing). However, with a slight blip in June and July, prices had been falling steadily during the first 9 months of 2010, increased slightly to February 2011 before declining throughout 2011, with only small blips in July and August. By December 2011 prices were 37% lower than in February 2011. After a slight recovery in January and February 2012, prices once again fell. By April 2012 prices were 25% below the 2011 average.</p><p>At this price level, unless producer prices are adjusted, significant financial losses will occur. This will then require a lower cocoa producer price from September/October 2012. This would then discourage production, reduce supplies and boost international prices. It can be argued that this is in line with the workings of the market.</p><p>If the aim is to stabilise producer prices to ensure long-term sustainable production (including not using child labour), at levels capable of meeting both growing overall global demand and increasing demand for high-quality cocoa, then it can be argued that there is a need for new contractual arrangements that provide greater price stability. Growing corporate concerns over the long-term supply of cocoa beans could potentially be used to explore options in this regard.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
